snippet.textDisplay: Here's a story that I'll remember Kobe by. My friend in Maine loved Kobe, and my friends Dad worked border control for an airport. Well Kobe was on the itinerary for a flight coming back from Italy. So he called my friend and told him Kobe was going to be landing there. Well my friends Dad asked Kobe if he'd spend a sec with his son for a pic. Well he ended up spending 20 minutes with him. Kobe gave a regular Joe 20 minutes of his busy life to a relative nobody. That meant everything to my friend.

snippet.textDisplay: Basketball today is good coz  there are a lot of really good players in the NBA. But it is clear that there is no one clear defining figure because I think no one has that mindset, that competitive instinct to be the best in the world. Everyone is a brand now and wants to be accepted. Kobe just wanted to compete, make everyone surrender and win. Now that he passed, it is a wake up call that we should never tire to seek out excellence not for recognition but the sheer need to excel. Even in death Kobe is showing us how to do things, how to attack life. Stats are just that. Stats. Kobe won in life. He showed us how to be a winner.

snippet.textDisplay: This all just seems so surreal. Like it can be taken back or fixed. The finality of it all is just devastating. Kobe was hailed as the heir to michael, and he certainly was. I caught the middle and end of jordans career and the entirety of Kobe's. Enormous shoes to fill and tremendous pressure, starting from HS. And he navigated it all almost flawlessly. He was too young and taken from his family and the world too soon. This was a tragedy above all else. Seeing people all over the world collectively grieve this loss is really overwhelming. It might have been just a game, but Kobe was the best in the world for most of my teens and 20's. Almost the way a song can take you back to a certain moment. Kobe dying is like losing part of my childhood, to sound selfish. God....... it just doesn't seem right.
